n won by capital. Contending that the aesthetic and political conditions are connected, Michaels argues that these artists’ new commitment to form and meaning is a way for them to depict the conditions that have taken US economic inequality from its lowest level, in 1968, to its highest level today. As Michaels demonstrates, these works of art, unimaginable without the postmodern critique of autonomy and intentionality, end up departing and dissenting from that critique in continually interesting and innovative ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArt criticism. 0aArt, AmericanxPhotography. 0aCritical theory. 0aFormalism (Art) 0aNeoliberalism. 0aPhotographyxPolitical aspects. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspects. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  aaesthetic.  aautonomy.  acapital.  aclass.  aform.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022621026140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226210438423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226210438/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles